                "name": "Jim Christmas",
                "href": "/profile/Jim-Christmas-1"
            },
            "answer_text": "Can you open your mouth a little further? Just a little more? Yes. It\u2019s just as I suspected; you\u2019re choking on a dictionary. How\u2019d you ever get it lodged in there like that? If you intend to use the sentence as you\u2019ve written it, you might add a comma after the word \u201crequest.\u201d The most awkward thing about the sentence is that if the reader requested the details, then the reader would know the purpose of those details. It seems silly to remind them that they asked for the details so they could consider them. But, it is grammatically correct\u2026 Ahem. I\u2019d urge you to consider re-writing it. The way it\u2019s written now makes it sound as if you\u2019re trying a little too hard to impress. I get the feeling that you\u2019re not comfortable with the words and it would make me want to double check everything you write for mistakes. That\u2019s coming from a guy who makes a LOT of mistakes in his writing. :-) Try, \u201cI\u2019ve attached the documents you asked for,\u201d or if you dare to go passive, \u201cThe documents you asked for are attached.\u201d The \u201cfor your consideration\u201d part might be better as, \u201cI\u2019m eager to get your input,\u201d or \u201cI\u2019d like to hear your thoughts on what I have so far.\u201d Of course, my advice is given without knowing what details you\u2019re attaching, or to whom you\u2019re writing. Maybe you\u2019re trying to get your bones interred at Westminster Abbey, in which case, \u201cAs per your request, I have attached the details for your consideration,\u201d might sound right to the recipients\u2026 That is, once they get enough dust out of their ears to hear you. ",
